â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“ shared/
    Purpose: Code shared between the frontend (React) and backend (Deno/Supabase Edge Functions).
    Details: Contains core services logic, utility functions, and type definitions used across the application.
    â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“ lib/
    â”‚   Purpose: Shared, low-level utility functions.
    â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ uuid-utils.ts
    â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Shared, canonical utility functions for validating and cleaning UUID strings.
    â”‚   â”‚   Details: Provides `isValidUuid(id)` to check format via regex. Provides `cleanUuid(id)` to sanitize by removing trailing spaces/digits before validation.
    â”‚   â”‚   Usage: Used across frontend/backend for UUID validation/sanitization, replacing previous duplicate implementations.
    â”‚   â”‚
    â”‚   â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“„ uuid.ts
    â”‚       Purpose: Shared, canonical implementation for generating UUID v4 strings.
    â”‚       Details: Uses `v4 as uuidv4` from the `uuid` npm package. Exports `generateId()`.
    â”‚       Usage: Standard way to generate unique IDs across the application (elements, sections, projects, etc.), replacing previous implementations.
    â”‚
    â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“ services/
    â”‚   Purpose: Core implementation logic for key application services, designed to be adapted for specific environments.
    â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ differ.ts
    â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Core, shared implementation for comparing two `EmailTemplate` (V2) objects and generating a detailed diff.
    â”‚   â”‚   Details: Contains `DifferCore` class. Requires Lodash instance. Methods `diffTemplates`, `diffSections`, `diffElements`, `diffProperties` compare structures based on IDs and properties, tracking additions, removals, modifications, moves. Returns `TemplateDiffResult`.
    â”‚   â”‚   Usage: Base class for frontend/backend adapters. Used by `generate-email-changes` backend function to compute pending changes.
    â”‚   â”‚
    â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ htmlGenerator.ts
    â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Core, shared implementation for generating HTML email strings from structured `EmailTemplate` (V2) objects.
    â”‚   â”‚   Details: Contains `HtmlGeneratorCore` class (implements `IHtmlGenerator`). Main `generate` method builds the document. Protected methods (`generateSectionHtml`, `generateElementHtml`, etc.) handle parts of the template. Follows adapter pattern. Includes robust HTML/CSS, resets, and email client compatibility fixes.
    â”‚   â”‚   Usage: Base class for frontend/backend adapters. Core logic for converting `EmailTemplateV2` to HTML.
    â”‚   â”‚
    â”‚   â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“„ semanticParser.ts
    â”‚       Purpose: Core, shared implementation logic for parsing HTML email strings into structured `EmailTemplate` (V2) objects.
    â”‚       Details: Contains `SemanticParserCore` class (implements `ISemanticParser`). Abstract `parse` method requires adapter implementation. Protected methods (`extractGlobalStyles`, `extractSectionStyles`, `extractElementProperties`, etc.) handle parsing logic. Includes helper utilities.
    â”‚       Usage: Base class for frontend/backend adapters. Enables converting raw HTML into the application's structured `EmailTemplateV2` format.
    â”‚
    â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“ types/
        Purpose: Shared TypeScript type definitions and configurations used across the entire application.
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“ config/
        â”‚   Purpose: Default configurations for shared entities.
        â”‚   â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“„ elementDefaults.ts
        â”‚       Purpose: Defines default configurations (styles, layout, properties) for all V2 email element types and provides a factory function.
        â”‚       Details: Exports `elementDefaults` constant mapping `ElementTypeV2` to default objects (using `@@PLACEHOLDER_...@@` markers). Exports `createNewElement(type, initialContent?)` factory function using `generateId` and deep copying defaults.
        â”‚       Usage: Used when creating new elements programmatically (AI/backend) or via UI (editor) to ensure consistency.
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ common.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines common, fundamental TypeScript types shared across the application.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `InteractionMode` union type (`'ask' | 'edit' | 'major'`).
        â”‚   Usage: Provides basic shared types, imported where needed (e.g., `EditorContext`).
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ diffs.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines TypeScript interfaces for representing the results of diffing email templates.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `PropertyChange`, `ElementDiff`, `SectionDiff`, `TemplateDiffResult`. Defines the structure returned by `DifferCore`.
        â”‚   Usage: Used by `DifferCore` service and consumers of diff results (e.g., `EditorContext` for pending changes).
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ editor.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines TypeScript types specific to the editor interface, primarily for chat/messaging.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `ChatMessage` interface (`id`, `project_id`, `role`, `content`, `timestamp`, `isError`).
        â”‚   Usage: Used by frontend components (`ChatInterface`, `EditorContext`) for chat data.
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ elements.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines all TypeScript types related to individual email elements within the V2 template structure.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `ElementType` union. Defines `EmailElementLayout` and specific property interfaces (`HeaderElementProperties`, `ImageElementProperties`, etc.) for all types. Exports the main `EmailElement` discriminated union.
        â”‚   Usage: Foundational types used by services, contexts, validation, and defaults for defining email content elements.
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ blog.ts                     # NEW: Defines types related to blog posts.
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines the frontend TypeScript interface for blog post data.
        â”‚   Details: Exports the `BlogPost` interface, mirroring the structure of the `blog_posts` Supabase table row.
        â”‚   Usage: Used by blog page components (`BlogIndexPage`, `BlogPostPage`) for type safety when handling fetched post data.
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ index.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Barrel file for the `src/shared/types` directory.
        â”‚   Details: Explicitly re-exports types from `elements.ts`, `sections.ts`, `template.ts`, `validators.ts`, `diffs.ts`, `blog.ts`.
        â”‚   Usage: Provides a single import point (`@shared/types`) for common shared types.
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ pendingChangeTypes.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines TypeScript types for representing proposed template changes awaiting approval.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `PendingChangeInput` (for creation) and `PendingChange` (for stored record, includes metadata).
        â”‚   Usage: Structures data for the pending changes workflow (backend functions, frontend context/UI).
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ sections.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines TypeScript types for email template sections.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `EmailSectionStyles` and `EmailSection` (id, elements array, styles) interfaces.
        â”‚   Usage: Part of the core `EmailTemplateV2` structure, used by services handling template structure.
        â”‚
        â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ template.ts
        â”‚   Purpose: Defines the top-level TypeScript types for the V2 email template structure.
        â”‚   Details: Exports `EmailGlobalStyles` and the main `EmailTemplate` (id, name, version, sections array, globalStyles) interfaces.
        â”‚   Usage: The central data structure for email content, used extensively by services, contexts, and backend functions.
        â”‚
        â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“„ validators.ts
            Purpose: Provides Zod schemas and a validation function specifically for the `EmailTemplate` V2 structure.
            Details: Defines comprehensive Zod schemas for all parts of `EmailTemplateV2`, including layouts, element properties, sections, global styles. Uses placeholders. Exports `validateEmailTemplateV2(templateData)` function using `safeParse`. Requires `version: 2`.
            Usage: Ensures data integrity, especially for AI-generated content. Used primarily in backend functions (e.g., `generate-email-changes`) before saving data.

### Database Types (`src/integrations/supabase/types.ts`)

This file, often generated/updated via Supabase CLI (`supabase gen types typescript`), contains the TypeScript definitions for the entire database schema (`Database` type). It ensures type safety when interacting with Supabase tables, views, and functions.

Key parts:
- `Json`: Defines the type for JSON/JSONB columns.
- `Database`: The main type, nesting definitions under `public` schema.
- `Tables`: Contains `Row`, `Insert`, `Update` types for each table (e.g., `projects`, `chat_messages`, `pending_changes`, `user_info`, `blog_posts`).
- `Tables<T>`, `TablesInsert<T>`, `TablesUpdate<T>`: Generic helper types for easier access to table row/insert/update types.

Usage: Imported by services (`projectService.ts`) and components that interact directly with Supabase data to ensure correct data shapes.

## AUTONOMOUS AI BLOG AGENT (PYTHON PROJECT)

ğŸ“ ai_blog_agent/
  Purpose: Contains the Python-based autonomous AI agent for blog content generation, research, and an approval workflow via Telegram.
  Details: This project is designed to be run as a standalone Python application. It uses Langchain for LLM orchestration and interacts with various APIs (OpenAI, Perplexity, Telegram, Supabase) to autonomously source news, generate blog content, and manage an interactive approval workflow via Telegram.
  Status: Core functionality for news sourcing, content generation, and Telegram-based approval workflow implemented. Ongoing refinements based on `AIAgentMap`.
  â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ AIAgentMap
  â”‚   Purpose: Detailed multi-phase roadmap and checklist for the development of the AI blog agent.
  â”‚   Details: Outlines phases from setup, manual trigger, Perplexity integration, Telegram approval, feedback handling, social media promotion, to deployment. Includes key decisions made.
  â”‚   Usage: Primary planning and tracking document for this sub-project.
  â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ .env
  â”‚   Purpose: Stores sensitive API keys and configuration variables for the AI blog agent.
  â”‚   Details: Contains `OPENAI_API_KEY`, `PERPLEXITY_API_KEY`, `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN`, `TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID`, and potentially Supabase function URLs/keys.
  â”‚   Usage: Loaded by `python-dotenv` in `main.py` to provide credentials to the application. This file is listed in `.gitignore` and should not be committed to version control.
  â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ config.yaml
  â”‚   Purpose: Main configuration file for the AI blog agent, storing non-sensitive settings, prompts, and parameters.
  â”‚   Details: Includes sections for Perplexity API settings (env var name, query params), OpenAI API settings (env var name, model choices), Telegram Bot settings (env var names), Supabase function details (URL), various prompts for LLM interaction (research, blog post generation, social media snippets), and job management settings (pending jobs file, max iterations).
  â”‚   Usage: Loaded by the agent to configure its behavior and interaction with LLMs and other services.
  â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ main.py
  â”‚   Purpose: Main orchestrator script for the AI Blog Agent.
  â”‚   Details: Initializes the agent, loads configurations, sets up Telegram bot (handlers, polling). Defines the core asynchronous workflow including fetching news topics, generating blog content (research, writing, formatting), and managing an interactive Telegram-based approval process (publish, delete, rewrite). Manages job context for multi-step interactions.
  â”‚   Usage: The primary entry point to run the AI blog agent (`python3 main.py`).
  â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ requirements.txt
  â”‚   Purpose: Lists all Python dependencies required for the AI blog agent.
  â”‚   Details: Includes `langchain`, `langchain-openai`, `openai`, `python-dotenv`, `requests`, `PyYAML`, `python-telegram-bot`.
  â”‚   Usage: Used to install dependencies into the virtual environment (`pip install -r requirements.txt`).
  â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“ modules/
  â”‚   Purpose: Contains various service modules, each responsible for a specific part of the agent's functionality.
  â”‚   Details: Follows a modular design to separate concerns.
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ __init__.py
  â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Makes the `modules` directory a Python package.
  â”‚   â”‚   Details: Currently empty.
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ job_manager.py
  â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Manages the state and context of ongoing blog post generation jobs, particularly for asynchronous Telegram interactions.
  â”‚   â”‚   Details: Provides functions (`store_job_context`, `get_job_context`, `pop_job_context`, `clear_job_context`) to handle an in-memory dictionary for storing job details (e.g., current draft data, user choices, next expected action). Supports a default job ID for single pending interaction.
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ notification_service.py
  â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Handles Telegram bot setup and communication.
  â”‚   â”‚   Details: Uses `python-telegram-bot`. Key functions include `create_bot_application` (initializes bot), `register_handlers` (maps commands, messages, callbacks to handler functions in `main.py`), `start_bot_polling`/`stop_bot_polling` (manages bot lifecycle), and `send_telegram_message` (sends formatted messages with optional inline keyboards). Also retrieves Telegram credentials.
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ perplexity_service.py
  â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Interacts with the Perplexity API for news sourcing and uses OpenAI for topic relevance assessment.
  â”‚   â”‚   Details: Implements `fetch_breaking_news_topic` which queries Perplexity for recent news based on configured keywords and then uses an OpenAI model to evaluate relevance and extract a concise blog topic. Loads Perplexity API and relevance check prompts from `config.yaml`.
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ research_service.py
  â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Conducts research on a given topic using an LLM (via Perplexity API direct call).
  â”‚   â”‚   Details: Implements `conduct_research` which takes a topic, queries the Perplexity API (model `llama-3.1-sonar-small-128k-online` by default) with a specific system prompt to gather information, and returns a synthesized research brief. Loads configuration from `config.yaml`.
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ ğŸ“„ supabase_service.py
  â”‚   â”‚   Purpose: Interacts with the Supabase backend for formatting blog post data and posting it.
  â”‚   â”‚   Details: Provides `format_for_supabase` to map generated blog components (title, slug, content, author_id, etc.) to the JSON payload expected by the Supabase Edge Function. Provides `post_blog_to_supabase` to send this payload to the `create-blog-post` Supabase Edge Function. Handles API responses and errors.
  â”‚   â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“„ writing_service.py
  â”‚       Purpose: Generates various components of a blog post (title, slug, content, excerpt) using LLM calls via Langchain, and can incorporate rewrite instructions.
  â”‚       Details: Implements `generate_blog_post_components` which orchestrates multiple OpenAI calls with specific prompts (from `config.yaml`) for each component. Accepts an initial research brief and optional user feedback for rewrites. Uses Langchain's `ChatOpenAI`.
  â””â”€â”€ ğŸ“ venv/
      Purpose: Python virtual environment for the `ai_blog_agent`.
      Details: Contains isolated Python interpreter and installed dependencies. This directory is typically gitignored.